./dev/plans/runs/11d-fix-1-20260517T173948Z.log:333:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01JYe1Lgqwdcy9T4eCJGPvXn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VELDndBYFUX4nrr5peRheN","name":"Edit","input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/tmp/fdb-11d-release-workflow-20260517T145932Z/dev/design/release.md","old_string":"Per `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not\ndone. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and\nruns an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is\ndeclared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `@fathomdb/...`\npublishes. Crate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`\nfollowed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh\nfixture database.","new_string":"Per `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not\ndone. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and\nruns an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is\ndeclared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `fathomdb` publishes.\nThe npm package is published as bare `fathomdb` (not a `@fathomdb/`\nscope) per 11d Blocker 7 — single brand across crates, wheel, and npm.\nCrate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`\nfollowed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh\nfixture database."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":871,"cache_read_input_tokens":55691,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":871},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"461792b1-c5f8-4800-9416-9dfcbd8f629a","uuid":"324c9a0c-62a9-4445-8097-031922256ed1"}
./dev/plans/runs/11d-fix-1-20260517T173948Z.log:336:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VELDndBYFUX4nrr5peRheN","type":"tool_result","content":"The file /tmp/fdb-11d-release-workflow-20260517T145932Z/dev/design/release.md has been updated successfully. (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"461792b1-c5f8-4800-9416-9dfcbd8f629a","uuid":"2ad11ca9-dd47-424d-8e51-1adcf615754a","timestamp":"2026-05-17T17:40:41.172Z","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-11d-release-workflow-20260517T145932Z/dev/design/release.md","oldString":"Per `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not\ndone. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and\nruns an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is\ndeclared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `@fathomdb/...`\npublishes. Crate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`\nfollowed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh\nfixture database.","newString":"Per `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not\ndone. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and\nruns an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is\ndeclared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `fathomdb` publishes.\nThe npm package is published as bare `fathomdb` (not a `@fathomdb/`\nscope) per 11d Blocker 7 — single brand across crates, wheel, and npm.\nCrate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`\nfollowed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh\nfixture database.","originalFile":"---\ntitle: Release Subsystem Design\ndate: 2026-05-12\ntarget_release: 0.6.0\ndesc: Version axes, tiered publish order, multi-registry publish discipline, and post-publish verification\nblast_radius: release workflows; REQ-047..REQ-052; scripts/set-version.sh; .github/workflows/release.yml; dev/plans/ci-deferred.md\nstatus: locked\n---\n\n# Release Design\n\nThis file owns release-gate mechanics: version axes, sibling-package\nco-tagging, tiered publish order, registry-installed smoke verification, and\natomic completion of the multi-registry publish flow.\n\n## Version axes (2026-05-12)\n\n0.6.0 ships **two independent version axes**, not one global workspace\nversion:\n\n- **Axis W (workspace).** Lockstep version for the runtime/binding/CLI\n  surface: `fathomdb`, `fathomdb-cli`, `fathomdb-engine`,\n  `fathomdb-query`, `fathomdb-schema`, `fathomdb-embedder`, plus the\n  Python (`src/python/`) and TypeScript (`src/ts/`) binding packages.\n- **Axis E (embedder-api).** Independent semver for\n  `fathomdb-embedder-api` only. Tagged and published on every workspace\n  release per REQ-048, but the embedder-api version bumps only when its\n  trait surface changes.\n\nRationale: `fathomdb-embedder-api` is the semver-stable trait surface\nper ADR-0.6.0-crate-topology (sibling-crate amendment) and\nADR-0.6.0-embedder-protocol. Lockstep-bumping it on every workspace\nrelease would create false version churn for downstream embedder\nconsumers pinning the trait, and would break the version-skew-resolution\nintent of REQ-047. Two axes preserve `fathomdb-embedder` /\n`fathomdb-embedder-api` consumer ergonomics without giving up workspace\nlockstep elsewhere.\n\nBoth axes share a single tag prefix (`v<axis-W-version>`) per release;\nthe embedder-api crate carries its independent `version` field in its\nown `Cargo.toml`. Version-consistency checks (`set-version.sh\n--check-files`) verify Axis W lockstep across all Axis-W manifests and\nverify Axis E sits at its independently declared version.\n\n## Tiered publish order\n\nThe publish order is a strict topological sort of the workspace crate\ndependency graph plus the two binding packages. Index-propagation sleeps\nsit between tiers (pattern from pre-0.6.0 `.github/workflows/release.yml`).\n\n| Tier | Targets                                                      | Why                                                                                                                                                                 |\n| ---- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| T1   | `fathomdb-embedder-api`                                      | Leaf. Axis E. Must publish first so every later crate can resolve it on crates.io.                                                                                  |\n| T2   | `fathomdb-schema`                                            | Leaf (no in-workspace deps beyond external crates).                                                                                                                 |\n| T3   | `fathomdb-query`                                             | Depends on `fathomdb-schema` (per ADR-0.6.0-crate-topology consequences) and `fathomdb-embedder-api` indirectly via retrieval glue.                                 |\n| T4   | `fathomdb-engine`                                            | Depends on T1+T2+T3. Largest crate; publishes only after its deps are resolvable on crates.io.                                                                      |\n| T5   | `fathomdb-embedder`                                          | Depends on `fathomdb-embedder-api` (Axis E). Independent of `fathomdb-engine`.                                                                                      |\n| T6   | `fathomdb`                                                   | Facade. Depends on `fathomdb-engine`.                                                                                                                               |\n| T7   | `fathomdb-cli`                                               | Depends on `fathomdb` facade per ADR-0.6.0-crate-topology amendment 2026-05-11.                                                                                     |\n| T8   | Python wheel (`src/python/`); TypeScript package (`src/ts/`) | Both wrap `fathomdb-engine` directly (PyO3 / napi-rs); they can publish in parallel after T4 resolves on crates.io. PyPI / npm publishing is independent of T5..T7. |\n\nCross-ecosystem gate: every tier must succeed before the next tier\nstarts. `all-builds-passed` gates Tier T1 from starting until every\nmatrix build for the release has produced an artifact (no \"publish T1\nwhile the napi-rs prebuild is still red\"). Cross-registry atomicity is\ncovered by the post-publish smoke step below.\n\nTier inter-step sleep: keep the pre-0.6.0 60-second\ncrates.io-index-propagation sleep between tiers. Without the sleep,\nlater tiers race the index and fail dependency resolution.\n\n## Sibling-package co-tagging\n\nPer REQ-048, `fathomdb-embedder-api` and `fathomdb-embedder` carry the\nsame git tag as the workspace release even though `fathomdb-embedder-api`\nruns on its own version axis. The tag prefix is workspace (Axis W);\n`fathomdb-embedder-api` records its independent version inside the tag\ncommit via its `Cargo.toml`.\n\n## Post-publish smoke\n\nPer `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not\ndone. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and\nruns an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is\ndeclared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `@fathomdb/...`\npublishes. Crate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`\nfollowed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh\nfixture database.\n\n## Sources\n\n- `dev/plans/ci-deferred.md` enumerates the pre-0.6.0 workflows being\n  restored.\n- `ADR-0.6.0-crate-topology` (incl. 2026-04-27 sibling amendment + 2026-05-11\n  CLI-via-facade amendment) owns the crate set.\n- `ADR-0.6.0-embedder-protocol` owns the `fathomdb-embedder-api` trait\n  stability posture.\n- REQ-047, REQ-048, REQ-049, REQ-050, REQ-052.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":82,"oldLines":8,"newStart":82,"newLines":10,"lines":[" Per `feedback_release_verification`, \"green CI + published wheel\" is not"," done. Release-evidence sweep installs the published wheel from PyPI and"," runs an end-to-end open + close + exit smoke before the release is","-declared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `@fathomdb/...`","-publishes. Crate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`","+declared signed. Equivalent npm smoke applies for `fathomdb` publishes.","+The npm package is published as bare `fathomdb` (not a `@fathomdb/`","+scope) per 11d Blocker 7 — single brand across crates, wheel, and npm.","+Crate publishes are smoked via `cargo install fathomdb-cli`"," followed by `fathomdb doctor check-integrity --json` against a fresh"," fixture database."," "]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
./dev/plans/runs/12-D-fix-1-20260517T192459Z.log:34:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RTJur3CEPVVJeUknKcDZaA","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Phase 12-D Review — codex gpt-5.4 verdict\n2\t\n3\tReviewer: `codex --model gpt-5.4 --sandbox read-only`.\n4\tTarget: branch `phase-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z` HEAD\n5\t`df7456b`.\n6\tBaseline: `23292b1` (close of Phase 11 + context-mgmt infra on\n7\t`0.6.0-rewrite`).\n8\tCherry-pick: `b70fbca` / `2a1c203` / `89c7300` on `0.6.0-rewrite`.\n9\tReview log: `dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.log`.\n10\t\n11\tSandbox note: reviewer could not write this file directly (read-only\n12\tsandbox). Main thread promoted the verbatim verdict from log line\n13\t~4750+.\n14\t\n15\t## Verdict: CONCERN\n16\t\n17\t### 1. [high] `probe_wal_sidecar` reads the entire WAL file on every open\n18\t\n19\tRefs:\n20\t\n21\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3024`\n22\t- `dev/acceptance.md:580`\n23\t\n24\t`probe_wal_sidecar()` uses `std::fs::read(&wal_path)` just to inspect\n25\tthe header. That makes `Engine.open` pull the full `-wal` sidecar\n26\tinto memory before SQLite does its own recovery work. On large\n27\tunclean-shutdown WALs, this is a real open-path latency and RSS\n28\tregression, and it directly risks the later AC-035 recovery-time\n29\tbudget. The schema-probe change is not the main latency concern\n30\there; the full-file WAL read is.\n31\t\n32\t### 2. [medium] AC-034b drops some trials from the p99 instead of measuring across all P-PWR-TRIALS\n33\t\n34\tRefs:\n35\t\n36\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:95`\n37\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:128`\n38\t- `dev/acceptance.md:568`\n39\t\n40\tThe harness records `lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>`, filters out\n41\t`None`, then computes p99 on the surviving subset. It only requires\n42\tthat 90% of trials have at least one surviving commit. That is\n43\tweaker than AC-034b's stated measurement \"report p99 across\n44\tP-PWR-TRIALS trials,\" and it means the parent never actually\n45\tguarantees that each victim committed at least one row before\n46\t`SIGKILL`.\n47\t\n48\t### 3. [medium] AC-035c's lock-release check is same-process, not sibling-process\n49\t\n50\tRefs:\n51\t\n52\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_open_path.rs:286`\n53\t- `dev/acceptance.md:608`\n54\t\n55\tThe test reacquires `.lock` with a second fd in the same process\n56\tand calls `flock` there. That is useful signal, but it is not the\n57\tdocumented measurement, which requires process A to fail open and\n58\tsibling process B to observe the lock as acquirable. Given the\n59\texplicit AC text, this is a partial proof, not the full contract.\n60\t\n61\t### 4. [low] The AC-034c ignored test is informative, but its body is a stub\n62\t\n63\tRefs:\n64\t\n65\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:238`\n66\t\n67\tThe `#[ignore]` reason is good and points at the missing VM/sysrq\n68\tsubstrate, but the body is intentionally empty. If someone clears\n69\t`#[ignore]` without implementing the harness, the test would pass\n70\tvacuously. This is not a current false green because it is ignored,\n71\tbut it is not a runnable placeholder.\n72\t\n73\t## What passed on inspection\n74\t\n75\t- The `open_locked` reorder is directionally correct: header and\n76\t  schema probing now happen before `journal_mode=WAL`, which\n77\t  prevents header/page-1 and schema-btree corruption from being\n78\t  misclassified as WAL replay.\n79\t- AC-035b is asserted per fixture for all four documented rows.\n80\t  Tests check exact `kind`, `stage`, `recovery_hint.code`, and\n81\t  `doc_anchor`. Code-stability test checks both string equality\n82\t  and pointer equality for the `&'static str`.\n83\t- `serial_guard()` is taken by every test in\n84\t  `durability_open_path.rs`, not just the AC-035c tests, so\n85\t  same-binary thread/fd contamination is actually serialized\n86\t  away.\n87\t- The thread/fd residue assertions are consistent with the engine\n88\t  lifecycle: reader threads and the projection runtime are only\n89\t  created after `open_locked` succeeds, so a corruption return\n90\t  from `open_locked` should not leave engine-started threads\n91\t  behind.\n92\t- No meaningful large-schema regression from `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM\n93\t  sqlite_schema` itself; schema surface is small and mostly fixed.\n94\t\n95\t## Reviewer process notes\n96\t\n97\t- Read `dev/acceptance.md`, `dev/design/recovery.md`,\n98\t  `dev/design/errors.md`, output JSON, all three commits, and the\n99\t  full `durability_open_path.rs`, `durability_soak.rs`,\n100\t  `tests/support/corruption.rs`, and `src/lib.rs` deltas.\n101\t- `dev/plans/prompts/12-D-durability-harnesses.md` not present in\n102\t  sparse worktree (out-of-tree by design); could not compare\n103\t  against prompt directly.\n104\t- `MEMORY.md` and `feedback_*.md` not present in worktree; TDD\n105\t  claim not independently verifiable from repo files. Git history\n106\t  bundles tests + engine changes together; red-before-green\n107\t  evidence not recoverable from commits alone.\n108\t- Review was static only; harnesses not executed in read-only\n109\t  sandbox.\n110\t\n111\t## Orchestrator triage\n112\t\n113\tAll four findings substantive and actionable. None\n114\tstructural/prompt-induced — orchestrator override not appropriate.\n115\t**Fix-1 remediation required.**\n116\t\n117\t- **Finding 1 (high)**: `probe_wal_sidecar` must only read the\n118\t  WAL header (first ~32 bytes — magic, page-size, salts), not the\n119\t  full file. SQLite's WAL header is fixed-layout; we don't need\n120\t  the frame data. Fix: replace `std::fs::read` with a bounded\n121\t  `File::open` + `read_exact(&mut [u8; HEADER_LEN])`. Add a test\n122\t  that opens a large fixture WAL (e.g. 10 MB) and asserts RSS\n123\t  delta is bounded.\n124\t- **Finding 2 (medium)**: ensure every victim commits at least\n125\t  one row before SIGKILL. Parent should signal \"ready\" via a\n126\t  per-trial sentinel file the child writes after its first commit\n127\t  lands; parent waits for sentinel before scheduling the kill.\n128\t  Then `lost_commit_ms` is `Some(_)` for every trial and p99 is\n129\t  computed across the full P-PWR-TRIALS=100 set.\n130\t- **Finding 3 (medium)**: replace in-process flock reacquire with\n131\t  true sibling-process check. Reuse Sub-2's test-binary-as-victim\n132\t  trick: spawn a child via `Command::new(current_exe())` with an\n133\t  env-var-gated entry point that attempts `flock` on `<db>.lock`\n134\t  and exits 0 if acquired / 1 if blocked. Parent invokes the\n135\t  AC-035c fixture, then asserts the child exits 0.\n136\t- **Finding 4 (low)**: AC-034c body must `panic!()` with the\n137\t  blocker text + a pointer to the missing substrate. Cleared\n138\t  `#[ignore]` without doing the work = test fails loudly instead\n139\t  of passing vacuously.\n140\t\n141\tSpawn 12-D-fix-1 (Opus 4.7 medium).\n142\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3dcf3508-c16d-46fb-9860-076600a60569","uuid":"8a514b4a-6977-4b51-b1bc-d23fd608c133","timestamp":"2026-05-17T19:25:05.498Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.md","content":"# Phase 12-D Review — codex gpt-5.4 verdict\n\nReviewer: `codex --model gpt-5.4 --sandbox read-only`.\nTarget: branch `phase-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z` HEAD\n`df7456b`.\nBaseline: `23292b1` (close of Phase 11 + context-mgmt infra on\n`0.6.0-rewrite`).\nCherry-pick: `b70fbca` / `2a1c203` / `89c7300` on `0.6.0-rewrite`.\nReview log: `dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.log`.\n\nSandbox note: reviewer could not write this file directly (read-only\nsandbox). Main thread promoted the verbatim verdict from log line\n~4750+.\n\n## Verdict: CONCERN\n\n### 1. [high] `probe_wal_sidecar` reads the entire WAL file on every open\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3024`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:580`\n\n`probe_wal_sidecar()` uses `std::fs::read(&wal_path)` just to inspect\nthe header. That makes `Engine.open` pull the full `-wal` sidecar\ninto memory before SQLite does its own recovery work. On large\nunclean-shutdown WALs, this is a real open-path latency and RSS\nregression, and it directly risks the later AC-035 recovery-time\nbudget. The schema-probe change is not the main latency concern\nhere; the full-file WAL read is.\n\n### 2. [medium] AC-034b drops some trials from the p99 instead of measuring across all P-PWR-TRIALS\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:95`\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:128`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:568`\n\nThe harness records `lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>`, filters out\n`None`, then computes p99 on the surviving subset. It only requires\nthat 90% of trials have at least one surviving commit. That is\nweaker than AC-034b's stated measurement \"report p99 across\nP-PWR-TRIALS trials,\" and it means the parent never actually\nguarantees that each victim committed at least one row before\n`SIGKILL`.\n\n### 3. [medium] AC-035c's lock-release check is same-process, not sibling-process\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_open_path.rs:286`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:608`\n\nThe test reacquires `.lock` with a second fd in the same process\nand calls `flock` there. That is useful signal, but it is not the\ndocumented measurement, which requires process A to fail open and\nsibling process B to observe the lock as acquirable. Given the\nexplicit AC text, this is a partial proof, not the full contract.\n\n### 4. [low] The AC-034c ignored test is informative, but its body is a stub\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:238`\n\nThe `#[ignore]` reason is good and points at the missing VM/sysrq\nsubstrate, but the body is intentionally empty. If someone clears\n`#[ignore]` without implementing the harness, the test would pass\nvacuously. This is not a current false green because it is ignored,\nbut it is not a runnable placeholder.\n\n## What passed on inspection\n\n- The `open_locked` reorder is directionally correct: header and\n  schema probing now happen before `journal_mode=WAL`, which\n  prevents header/page-1 and schema-btree corruption from being\n  misclassified as WAL replay.\n- AC-035b is asserted per fixture for all four documented rows.\n  Tests check exact `kind`, `stage`, `recovery_hint.code`, and\n  `doc_anchor`. Code-stability test checks both string equality\n  and pointer equality for the `&'static str`.\n- `serial_guard()` is taken by every test in\n  `durability_open_path.rs`, not just the AC-035c tests, so\n  same-binary thread/fd contamination is actually serialized\n  away.\n- The thread/fd residue assertions are consistent with the engine\n  lifecycle: reader threads and the projection runtime are only\n  created after `open_locked` succeeds, so a corruption return\n  from `open_locked` should not leave engine-started threads\n  behind.\n- No meaningful large-schema regression from `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM\n  sqlite_schema` itself; schema surface is small and mostly fixed.\n\n## Reviewer process notes\n\n- Read `dev/acceptance.md`, `dev/design/recovery.md`,\n  `dev/design/errors.md`, output JSON, all three commits, and the\n  full `durability_open_path.rs`, `durability_soak.rs`,\n  `tests/support/corruption.rs`, and `src/lib.rs` deltas.\n- `dev/plans/prompts/12-D-durability-harnesses.md` not present in\n  sparse worktree (out-of-tree by design); could not compare\n  against prompt directly.\n- `MEMORY.md` and `feedback_*.md` not present in worktree; TDD\n  claim not independently verifiable from repo files. Git history\n  bundles tests + engine changes together; red-before-green\n  evidence not recoverable from commits alone.\n- Review was static only; harnesses not executed in read-only\n  sandbox.\n\n## Orchestrator triage\n\nAll four findings substantive and actionable. None\nstructural/prompt-induced — orchestrator override not appropriate.\n**Fix-1 remediation required.**\n\n- **Finding 1 (high)**: `probe_wal_sidecar` must only read the\n  WAL header (first ~32 bytes — magic, page-size, salts), not the\n  full file. SQLite's WAL header is fixed-layout; we don't need\n  the frame data. Fix: replace `std::fs::read` with a bounded\n  `File::open` + `read_exact(&mut [u8; HEADER_LEN])`. Add a test\n  that opens a large fixture WAL (e.g. 10 MB) and asserts RSS\n  delta is bounded.\n- **Finding 2 (medium)**: ensure every victim commits at least\n  one row before SIGKILL. Parent should signal \"ready\" via a\n  per-trial sentinel file the child writes after its first commit\n  lands; parent waits for sentinel before scheduling the kill.\n  Then `lost_commit_ms` is `Some(_)` for every trial and p99 is\n  computed across the full P-PWR-TRIALS=100 set.\n- **Finding 3 (medium)**: replace in-process flock reacquire with\n  true sibling-process check. Reuse Sub-2's test-binary-as-victim\n  trick: spawn a child via `Command::new(current_exe())` with an\n  env-var-gated entry point that attempts `flock` on `<db>.lock`\n  and exits 0 if acquired / 1 if blocked. Parent invokes the\n  AC-035c fixture, then asserts the child exits 0.\n- **Finding 4 (low)**: AC-034c body must `panic!()` with the\n  blocker text + a pointer to the missing substrate. Cleared\n  `#[ignore]` without doing the work = test fails loudly instead\n  of passing vacuously.\n\nSpawn 12-D-fix-1 (Opus 4.7 medium).\n","numLines":142,"startLine":1,"totalLines":142}}}
./dev/plans/runs/12-D-fix-1-20260517T192459Z.log:77:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013EcpDM1FXXtUZcSzx75wgk","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t//! Power-cut + OS-crash durability harnesses (AC-034a / AC-034b / AC-034c).\n2\t//!\n3\t//! Both bodies are gated on `AGENT_LONG=1` per `tests/perf_gates.rs`\n4\t//! precedent: `agent-verify` skips the long run, the dedicated soak\n5\t//! pipeline opts in. The harness is NOT a soak (open-ended) — it runs\n6\t//! `P-PWR-TRIALS = 100` (AC-034a/b) or `P-OS-TRIALS = 50` (AC-034c)\n7\t//! deterministic trials and asserts the bounds in `dev/acceptance.md`.\n8\t//!\n9\t//! Substrate notes:\n10\t//!   - Power-cut victim is the test binary itself, re-entered through\n11\t//!     `Command::new(current_exe())` with an env-var sentinel that\n12\t//!     routes execution to `_power_cut_victim_entry` (test-binary-as-\n13\t//!     victim trick). No dedicated `cargo-bin` victim is required.\n14\t//!   - OS-crash (AC-034c) requires a VM image + sysrq trigger per\n15\t//!     `dev/acceptance.md` § AC-034c fixture; that substrate does not\n16\t//!     exist in this repo, so the AC-034c body surfaces as a runtime\n17\t//!     blocker and the trial loop returns early. See\n18\t//!     `dev/plans/runs/12-D-durability-harnesses-output.json`.\n19\t\n20\tuse std::path::PathBuf;\n21\tuse std::process::{Command, Stdio};\n22\tuse std::time::{Duration, Instant, SystemTime, UNIX_EPOCH};\n23\t\n24\tuse fathomdb_engine::{Engine, PreparedWrite};\n25\tuse tempfile::TempDir;\n26\t\n27\tfn long_run_enabled() -> bool {\n28\t    std::env::var_os(\"AGENT_LONG\").is_some()\n29\t}\n30\t\n31\tconst P_PWR_TRIALS: usize = 100;\n32\tconst AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS: u128 = 100;\n33\t// Per-trial wait between victim startup and SIGKILL. Drawn uniformly\n34\t// from [PWR_MIN_KILL_MS, PWR_MAX_KILL_MS) so kills land at varied\n35\t// commit-cycle phases per AC-034a/b fixture spec.\n36\tconst PWR_MIN_KILL_MS: u64 = 30;\n37\tconst PWR_MAX_KILL_MS: u64 = 180;\n38\t// Time budget for the victim child to die after SIGKILL before we\n39\t// declare the trial degenerate. Generous; SIGKILL is immediate.\n40\tconst VICTIM_REAP_BUDGET: Duration = Duration::from_secs(5);\n41\t\n42\t// ── Victim entry-point ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n43\t\n44\t/// Test-binary-as-victim entry. Re-invoked from\n45\t/// `Command::new(current_exe()) --exact --ignored _power_cut_victim_entry`\n46\t/// with `FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB` set. Without the env var the test\n47\t/// is a no-op so plain `cargo test --test durability_soak -- --ignored`\n48\t/// (no env var) is still safe.\n49\t#[test]\n50\t#[ignore = \"test-binary-as-victim entry-point for the AC-034a/b power-cut harness\"]\n51\tfn _power_cut_victim_entry() {\n52\t    let Some(db_path_os) = std::env::var_os(\"FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB\") else {\n53\t        return;\n54\t    };\n55\t    let path = PathBuf::from(db_path_os);\n56\t    let opened = Engine::open(&path).expect(\"victim engine open\");\n57\t    // Commit single-row writes carrying the wall-clock timestamp of the\n58\t    // commit in the body field. The parent recovers the maximum body\n59\t    // value after kill — that is the last-surviving-commit timestamp\n60\t    // per AC-034b measurement protocol.\n61\t    loop {\n62\t        let body = micros_since_epoch().to_string();\n63\t        opened\n64\t            .engine\n65\t            .write(&[PreparedWrite::Node { kind: \"doc\".to_string(), body, source_id: None }])\n66\t            .expect(\"victim write\");\n67\t    }\n68\t}\n69\t\n70\tfn micros_since_epoch() -> u128 {\n71\t    SystemTime::now().duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH).expect(\"clock\").as_micros()\n72\t}\n73\t\n74\t// ── AC-034a + AC-034b: power-cut harness ────────────────────────────────────\n75\t\n76\t#[test]\n77\tfn ac_034a_and_b_power_cut_zero_corruption_and_p99_lost_commit() {\n78\t    if !long_run_enabled() {\n79\t        eprintln!(\"AC-034a/b skipped (AGENT_LONG not set)\");\n80\t        return;\n81\t    }\n82\t    let outcomes = run_power_cut_trials(P_PWR_TRIALS);\n83\t\n84\t    // AC-034a: integrity_check == \"ok\" on every trial.\n85\t    let bad: Vec<_> = outcomes.iter().filter(|o| o.integrity != \"ok\").collect();\n86\t    assert!(\n87\t        bad.is_empty(),\n88\t        \"AC-034a: {} of {} trials returned non-ok integrity_check: {:?}\",\n89\t        bad.len(),\n90\t        outcomes.len(),\n91\t        bad,\n92\t    );\n93\t\n94\t    // AC-034b: p99 lost-commit duration ≤ 100 ms.\n95\t    let mut lost: Vec<u128> = outcomes.iter().filter_map(|o| o.lost_commit_ms).collect();\n96\t    assert!(\n97\t        lost.len() >= (outcomes.len() * 9 / 10),\n98\t        \"AC-034b: only {} of {} trials yielded a surviving commit; \\\n99\t         the harness is killing the victim before any write lands\",\n100\t        lost.len(),\n101\t        outcomes.len(),\n102\t    );\n103\t    lost.sort_unstable();\n104\t    let p99_index = ((lost.len() as f64 * 0.99).ceil() as usize).saturating_sub(1);\n105\t    let p99 = lost[p99_index];\n106\t    eprintln!(\"AC-034a: integrity_check ok on {}/{} trials\", outcomes.len(), outcomes.len());\n107\t    eprintln!(\n108\t        \"AC-034b: lost-commit ms — n={}, min={}, median={}, p99={}\",\n109\t        lost.len(),\n110\t        lost[0],\n111\t        lost[lost.len() / 2],\n112\t        p99,\n113\t    );\n114\t    assert!(\n115\t        p99 <= AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS,\n116\t        \"AC-034b: lost-commit p99 = {} ms > {} ms budget\",\n117\t        p99,\n118\t        AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS,\n119\t    );\n120\t}\n121\t\n122\t#[derive(Debug)]\n123\tstruct TrialOutcome {\n124\t    integrity: String,\n125\t    lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>,\n126\t}\n127\t\n128\tfn run_power_cut_trials(trials: usize) -> Vec<TrialOutcome> {\n129\t    let exe = std::env::current_exe().expect(\"current_exe\");\n130\t    let mut outcomes = Vec::with_capacity(trials);\n131\t    for trial in 0..trials {\n132\t        let dir = TempDir::new().expect(\"tempdir\");\n133\t        let db_path = dir.path().join(\"power-cut.sqlite\");\n134\t\n135\t        let mut child = Command::new(&exe)\n136\t            .args([\"--exact\", \"--ignored\", \"_power_cut_victim_entry\"])\n137\t            .env(\"FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB\", &db_path)\n138\t            // Per-trial stdio drop; the parent does not parse victim\n139\t            // output, and leaving stdout connected to the parent test\n140\t            // would interleave with `cargo test` framing.\n141\t            .stdout(Stdio::null())\n142\t            .stderr(Stdio::null())\n143\t            .spawn()\n144\t            .expect(\"spawn victim\");\n145\t        let pid = child.id() as i32;\n146\t\n147\t        // Allow the child to start writing before we kill it. Without\n148\t        // a floor, the kill races the engine-open path and most trials\n149\t        // produce zero surviving commits.\n150\t        let sleep_ms = trial_sleep_ms(trial);\n151\t        std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms));\n152\t\n153\t        let kill_micros = micros_since_epoch();\n154\t        // SAFETY: `pid` is owned by `child` and we have not yet\n155\t        // wait()-ed for it. SIGKILL on a still-running PID is defined.\n156\t        let kill_rc = unsafe { libc::kill(pid, libc::SIGKILL) };\n157\t        if kill_rc != 0 {\n158\t            panic!(\"trial {trial}: SIGKILL failed: {}\", std::io::Error::last_os_error());\n159\t        }\n160\t\n161\t        // Reap the child. SIGKILL is immediate, but `wait` is the only\n162\t        // way to release the zombie + confirm the process is gone\n163\t        // before we touch the WAL file from the parent.\n164\t        wait_with_budget(&mut child, VICTIM_REAP_BUDGET, trial);\n165\t\n166\t        let last_commit_micros = read_last_commit_micros(&db_path);\n167\t        let integrity = run_integrity_check(&db_path);\n168\t        let lost_commit_ms = last_commit_micros.map(|last| {\n169\t            // `kill_micros >= last` holds by construction (last is read\n170\t            // from a committed row, kill_micros samples after spawn).\n171\t            // Saturating sub guards against clock jumps under load.\n172\t            kill_micros.saturating_sub(last) / 1_000\n173\t        });\n174\t        outcomes.push(TrialOutcome { integrity, lost_commit_ms });\n175\t    }\n176\t    outcomes\n177\t}\n178\t\n179\tfn trial_sleep_ms(trial: usize) -> u64 {\n180\t    // Deterministic linear-congruential sequence keyed off the trial\n181\t    // index; trials remain reproducible across runs while still\n182\t    // sweeping the kill point across the commit cycle.\n183\t    let mixed = (trial as u64)\n184\t        .wrapping_mul(6_364_136_223_846_793_005)\n185\t        .wrapping_add(1_442_695_040_888_963_407);\n186\t    let range = PWR_MAX_KILL_MS - PWR_MIN_KILL_MS;\n187\t    PWR_MIN_KILL_MS + (mixed % range)\n188\t}\n189\t\n190\tfn wait_with_budget(child: &mut std::process::Child, budget: Duration, trial: usize) {\n191\t    let started = Instant::now();\n192\t    loop {\n193\t        match child.try_wait() {\n194\t            Ok(Some(_)) => return,\n195\t            Ok(None) => {\n196\t                if started.elapsed() > budget {\n197\t                    panic!(\"trial {trial}: victim did not exit within {:?} after SIGKILL\", budget);\n198\t                }\n199\t                std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(5));\n200\t            }\n201\t            Err(err) => panic!(\"trial {trial}: wait failed: {err}\"),\n202\t        }\n203\t    }\n204\t}\n205\t\n206\tfn read_last_commit_micros(db_path: &std::path::Path) -> Option<u128> {\n207\t    // Read via the engine to confirm the engine itself can recover the\n208\t    // killed database; raw rusqlite on a half-recovered DB might paper\n209\t    // over an open-path defect.\n210\t    let opened = Engine::open(db_path).expect(\"post-kill engine open\");\n211\t    let path = opened.engine.path().to_path_buf();\n212\t    opened.engine.close().expect(\"post-kill close\");\n213\t    drop(opened);\n214\t\n215\t    let conn = rusqlite::Connection::open(&path).expect(\"post-kill rusqlite open\");\n216\t    // Bodies are decimal microsecond timestamps; ordering by CAST keeps\n217\t    // semantics correct if the column is TEXT-affinity.\n218\t    let max: Option<String> = conn\n219\t        .query_row(\n220\t            \"SELECT body FROM canonical_nodes\n221\t              WHERE kind = 'doc'\n222\t              ORDER BY CAST(body AS INTEGER) DESC LIMIT 1\",\n223\t            [],\n224\t            |row| row.get(0),\n225\t        )\n226\t        .ok();\n227\t    max.and_then(|raw| raw.parse::<u128>().ok())\n228\t}\n229\t\n230\tfn run_integrity_check(db_path: &std::path::Path) -> String {\n231\t    let conn = rusqlite::Connection::open(db_path).expect(\"integrity rusqlite open\");\n232\t    conn.query_row(\"PRAGMA integrity_check\", [], |row| row.get::<_, String>(0))\n233\t        .unwrap_or_else(|err| format!(\"integrity_check query failed: {err}\"))\n234\t}\n235\t\n236\t// ── AC-034c: OS-crash harness ───────────────────────────────────────────────\n237\t\n238\t#[test]\n239\t#[ignore = \"AC-034c blocked on missing VM/sysrq fixture; see Phase 12-D \\\n240\t            output JSON (blocker-3). Do NOT clear the #[ignore] until \\\n241\t            the VM image lands in dev/test-plan.md.\"]\n242\tfn ac_034c_os_crash_zero_committed_tx_loss() {\n243\t    // Intentionally empty body. The `#[ignore]` carries the blocker so\n244\t    // `cargo test --release --test durability_soak ac_034c` reports\n245\t    // \"1 ignored\" — visible in CI logs, not a silent skip — without\n246\t    // pretending to verify the AC. Substituting `kill -9` for an OS\n247\t    // crash would be silent AC weakening (per\n248\t    // `feedback_reliability_principles.md` no-punt rule).\n249\t    //\n250\t    // To unblock: land the KVM image + `echo c > /proc/sysrq-trigger`\n251\t    // workflow per `dev/acceptance.md` § AC-034c fixture, clear the\n252\t    // `#[ignore]`, and wire trial loop here following the AC-034a/b\n253\t    // shape above.\n254\t}\n255\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3dcf3508-c16d-46fb-9860-076600a60569","uuid":"2b0e9def-2a48-48a7-9e26-f6c73fb158ba","timestamp":"2026-05-17T19:25:10.860Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs","content":"//! Power-cut + OS-crash durability harnesses (AC-034a / AC-034b / AC-034c).\n//!\n//! Both bodies are gated on `AGENT_LONG=1` per `tests/perf_gates.rs`\n//! precedent: `agent-verify` skips the long run, the dedicated soak\n//! pipeline opts in. The harness is NOT a soak (open-ended) — it runs\n//! `P-PWR-TRIALS = 100` (AC-034a/b) or `P-OS-TRIALS = 50` (AC-034c)\n//! deterministic trials and asserts the bounds in `dev/acceptance.md`.\n//!\n//! Substrate notes:\n//!   - Power-cut victim is the test binary itself, re-entered through\n//!     `Command::new(current_exe())` with an env-var sentinel that\n//!     routes execution to `_power_cut_victim_entry` (test-binary-as-\n//!     victim trick). No dedicated `cargo-bin` victim is required.\n//!   - OS-crash (AC-034c) requires a VM image + sysrq trigger per\n//!     `dev/acceptance.md` § AC-034c fixture; that substrate does not\n//!     exist in this repo, so the AC-034c body surfaces as a runtime\n//!     blocker and the trial loop returns early. See\n//!     `dev/plans/runs/12-D-durability-harnesses-output.json`.\n\nuse std::path::PathBuf;\nuse std::process::{Command, Stdio};\nuse std::time::{Duration, Instant, SystemTime, UNIX_EPOCH};\n\nuse fathomdb_engine::{Engine, PreparedWrite};\nuse tempfile::TempDir;\n\nfn long_run_enabled() -> bool {\n    std::env::var_os(\"AGENT_LONG\").is_some()\n}\n\nconst P_PWR_TRIALS: usize = 100;\nconst AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS: u128 = 100;\n// Per-trial wait between victim startup and SIGKILL. Drawn uniformly\n// from [PWR_MIN_KILL_MS, PWR_MAX_KILL_MS) so kills land at varied\n// commit-cycle phases per AC-034a/b fixture spec.\nconst PWR_MIN_KILL_MS: u64 = 30;\nconst PWR_MAX_KILL_MS: u64 = 180;\n// Time budget for the victim child to die after SIGKILL before we\n// declare the trial degenerate. Generous; SIGKILL is immediate.\nconst VICTIM_REAP_BUDGET: Duration = Duration::from_secs(5);\n\n// ── Victim entry-point ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n/// Test-binary-as-victim entry. Re-invoked from\n/// `Command::new(current_exe()) --exact --ignored _power_cut_victim_entry`\n/// with `FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB` set. Without the env var the test\n/// is a no-op so plain `cargo test --test durability_soak -- --ignored`\n/// (no env var) is still safe.\n#[test]\n#[ignore = \"test-binary-as-victim entry-point for the AC-034a/b power-cut harness\"]\nfn _power_cut_victim_entry() {\n    let Some(db_path_os) = std::env::var_os(\"FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB\") else {\n        return;\n    };\n    let path = PathBuf::from(db_path_os);\n    let opened = Engine::open(&path).expect(\"victim engine open\");\n    // Commit single-row writes carrying the wall-clock timestamp of the\n    // commit in the body field. The parent recovers the maximum body\n    // value after kill — that is the last-surviving-commit timestamp\n    // per AC-034b measurement protocol.\n    loop {\n        let body = micros_since_epoch().to_string();\n        opened\n            .engine\n            .write(&[PreparedWrite::Node { kind: \"doc\".to_string(), body, source_id: None }])\n            .expect(\"victim write\");\n    }\n}\n\nfn micros_since_epoch() -> u128 {\n    SystemTime::now().duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH).expect(\"clock\").as_micros()\n}\n\n// ── AC-034a + AC-034b: power-cut harness ────────────────────────────────────\n\n#[test]\nfn ac_034a_and_b_power_cut_zero_corruption_and_p99_lost_commit() {\n    if !long_run_enabled() {\n        eprintln!(\"AC-034a/b skipped (AGENT_LONG not set)\");\n        return;\n    }\n    let outcomes = run_power_cut_trials(P_PWR_TRIALS);\n\n    // AC-034a: integrity_check == \"ok\" on every trial.\n    let bad: Vec<_> = outcomes.iter().filter(|o| o.integrity != \"ok\").collect();\n    assert!(\n        bad.is_empty(),\n        \"AC-034a: {} of {} trials returned non-ok integrity_check: {:?}\",\n        bad.len(),\n        outcomes.len(),\n        bad,\n    );\n\n    // AC-034b: p99 lost-commit duration ≤ 100 ms.\n    let mut lost: Vec<u128> = outcomes.iter().filter_map(|o| o.lost_commit_ms).collect();\n    assert!(\n        lost.len() >= (outcomes.len() * 9 / 10),\n        \"AC-034b: only {} of {} trials yielded a surviving commit; \\\n         the harness is killing the victim before any write lands\",\n        lost.len(),\n        outcomes.len(),\n    );\n    lost.sort_unstable();\n    let p99_index = ((lost.len() as f64 * 0.99).ceil() as usize).saturating_sub(1);\n    let p99 = lost[p99_index];\n    eprintln!(\"AC-034a: integrity_check ok on {}/{} trials\", outcomes.len(), outcomes.len());\n    eprintln!(\n        \"AC-034b: lost-commit ms — n={}, min={}, median={}, p99={}\",\n        lost.len(),\n        lost[0],\n        lost[lost.len() / 2],\n        p99,\n    );\n    assert!(\n        p99 <= AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS,\n        \"AC-034b: lost-commit p99 = {} ms > {} ms budget\",\n        p99,\n        AC_034B_P99_BUDGET_MS,\n    );\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct TrialOutcome {\n    integrity: String,\n    lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>,\n}\n\nfn run_power_cut_trials(trials: usize) -> Vec<TrialOutcome> {\n    let exe = std::env::current_exe().expect(\"current_exe\");\n    let mut outcomes = Vec::with_capacity(trials);\n    for trial in 0..trials {\n        let dir = TempDir::new().expect(\"tempdir\");\n        let db_path = dir.path().join(\"power-cut.sqlite\");\n\n        let mut child = Command::new(&exe)\n            .args([\"--exact\", \"--ignored\", \"_power_cut_victim_entry\"])\n            .env(\"FATHOMDB_POWER_CUT_VICTIM_DB\", &db_path)\n            // Per-trial stdio drop; the parent does not parse victim\n            // output, and leaving stdout connected to the parent test\n            // would interleave with `cargo test` framing.\n            .stdout(Stdio::null())\n            .stderr(Stdio::null())\n            .spawn()\n            .expect(\"spawn victim\");\n        let pid = child.id() as i32;\n\n        // Allow the child to start writing before we kill it. Without\n        // a floor, the kill races the engine-open path and most trials\n        // produce zero surviving commits.\n        let sleep_ms = trial_sleep_ms(trial);\n        std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(sleep_ms));\n\n        let kill_micros = micros_since_epoch();\n        // SAFETY: `pid` is owned by `child` and we have not yet\n        // wait()-ed for it. SIGKILL on a still-running PID is defined.\n        let kill_rc = unsafe { libc::kill(pid, libc::SIGKILL) };\n        if kill_rc != 0 {\n            panic!(\"trial {trial}: SIGKILL failed: {}\", std::io::Error::last_os_error());\n        }\n\n        // Reap the child. SIGKILL is immediate, but `wait` is the only\n        // way to release the zombie + confirm the process is gone\n        // before we touch the WAL file from the parent.\n        wait_with_budget(&mut child, VICTIM_REAP_BUDGET, trial);\n\n        let last_commit_micros = read_last_commit_micros(&db_path);\n        let integrity = run_integrity_check(&db_path);\n        let lost_commit_ms = last_commit_micros.map(|last| {\n            // `kill_micros >= last` holds by construction (last is read\n            // from a committed row, kill_micros samples after spawn).\n            // Saturating sub guards against clock jumps under load.\n            kill_micros.saturating_sub(last) / 1_000\n        });\n        outcomes.push(TrialOutcome { integrity, lost_commit_ms });\n    }\n    outcomes\n}\n\nfn trial_sleep_ms(trial: usize) -> u64 {\n    // Deterministic linear-congruential sequence keyed off the trial\n    // index; trials remain reproducible across runs while still\n    // sweeping the kill point across the commit cycle.\n    let mixed = (trial as u64)\n        .wrapping_mul(6_364_136_223_846_793_005)\n        .wrapping_add(1_442_695_040_888_963_407);\n    let range = PWR_MAX_KILL_MS - PWR_MIN_KILL_MS;\n    PWR_MIN_KILL_MS + (mixed % range)\n}\n\nfn wait_with_budget(child: &mut std::process::Child, budget: Duration, trial: usize) {\n    let started = Instant::now();\n    loop {\n        match child.try_wait() {\n            Ok(Some(_)) => return,\n            Ok(None) => {\n                if started.elapsed() > budget {\n                    panic!(\"trial {trial}: victim did not exit within {:?} after SIGKILL\", budget);\n                }\n                std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(5));\n            }\n            Err(err) => panic!(\"trial {trial}: wait failed: {err}\"),\n        }\n    }\n}\n\nfn read_last_commit_micros(db_path: &std::path::Path) -> Option<u128> {\n    // Read via the engine to confirm the engine itself can recover the\n    // killed database; raw rusqlite on a half-recovered DB might paper\n    // over an open-path defect.\n    let opened = Engine::open(db_path).expect(\"post-kill engine open\");\n    let path = opened.engine.path().to_path_buf();\n    opened.engine.close().expect(\"post-kill close\");\n    drop(opened);\n\n    let conn = rusqlite::Connection::open(&path).expect(\"post-kill rusqlite open\");\n    // Bodies are decimal microsecond timestamps; ordering by CAST keeps\n    // semantics correct if the column is TEXT-affinity.\n    let max: Option<String> = conn\n        .query_row(\n            \"SELECT body FROM canonical_nodes\n              WHERE kind = 'doc'\n              ORDER BY CAST(body AS INTEGER) DESC LIMIT 1\",\n            [],\n            |row| row.get(0),\n        )\n        .ok();\n    max.and_then(|raw| raw.parse::<u128>().ok())\n}\n\nfn run_integrity_check(db_path: &std::path::Path) -> String {\n    let conn = rusqlite::Connection::open(db_path).expect(\"integrity rusqlite open\");\n    conn.query_row(\"PRAGMA integrity_check\", [], |row| row.get::<_, String>(0))\n        .unwrap_or_else(|err| format!(\"integrity_check query failed: {err}\"))\n}\n\n// ── AC-034c: OS-crash harness ───────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n#[test]\n#[ignore = \"AC-034c blocked on missing VM/sysrq fixture; see Phase 12-D \\\n            output JSON (blocker-3). Do NOT clear the #[ignore] until \\\n            the VM image lands in dev/test-plan.md.\"]\nfn ac_034c_os_crash_zero_committed_tx_loss() {\n    // Intentionally empty body. The `#[ignore]` carries the blocker so\n    // `cargo test --release --test durability_soak ac_034c` reports\n    // \"1 ignored\" — visible in CI logs, not a silent skip — without\n    // pretending to verify the AC. Substituting `kill -9` for an OS\n    // crash would be silent AC weakening (per\n    // `feedback_reliability_principles.md` no-punt rule).\n    //\n    // To unblock: land the KVM image + `echo c > /proc/sysrq-trigger`\n    // workflow per `dev/acceptance.md` § AC-034c fixture, clear the\n    // `#[ignore]`, and wire trial loop here following the AC-034a/b\n    // shape above.\n}\n","numLines":255,"startLine":1,"totalLines":255}}}
