codex
The patch breaks the Mem0 baseline by making its config builder impossible to call from the existing adapter, and it misreports the new re-pin identity in eval outputs. Those issues affect the slice’s intended live parity runs and result provenance.

Full review comments:

- [P1] Keep Mem0 config callable from `Mem0OSSAdapter.try_build()` — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/mem0_local.py:48-52
  Making `corpus_hash` a required keyword here breaks the only production call site: `Mem0OSSAdapter.try_build()` still invokes `build_local_mem0_config(**kwargs)` with just `api_key`/model/base-url overrides. That now raises `TypeError`, which `try_build()` swallows and reports as “mem0 unavailable”, so every live R2 run skips the Mem0 arm even when `mem0ai` and the local backend are installed.

- [P2] Preserve the re-pinned file’s `qrels_version` in `from_repin_gold()` — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/r2_parity_eval.py:655-660
  After this change the gold’s identity is `repin-{repin_hash[:8]}`, but `R2Harness.from_repin_gold()` still synthesizes `qrels_version` from `corpus_hash`. Because the LME `corpus_hash` is intentionally stable across repins, any eval built from a re-pinned gold file now reports the wrong version tag (for the checked-in file, `repin-1859817a` instead of `repin-2916cace`), which makes distinct gold revisions indistinguishable in downstream results and audit logs.
